{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Accessibility Regulations\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Web accessibility is receiving significant attention ahead of the April 26, 2026 deadline set by the ADA Title II Web Accessibility Rule. Finalized by the Department of Justice in April 2024, the rule explicitly requires state and local governments to meet WCAG 2.1 Level AA for their websites and mobile applications. The deadline applies to entities serving 50,000 or more people; smaller entities have until April 26, 2027.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For many organizations this is a new obligation. For NGRREC and its IDNR websites, it is not. Because our projects receive federal financial assistance, accessibility has been a legal requirement for years. Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act extends accessibility obligations to any organization receiving federal funding, and compliance is interpreted through the standard established by the 2017 Section 508 Refresh: WCAG 2.0 Level AA.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 WCAG 2.1 is a strict superset of WCAG 2.0 \u8212- every criterion in 2.0 is preserved in 2.1, with additional criteria addressing mobile usability and cognitive accessibility. A site that fully meets WCAG 2.0 AA is already close to 2.1 AA compliance. We have been using 2.1 AA for our own assessments for several years. For our sites, the the current deadline has been an opportunity to tidy up across the board and ensure the upgrade to the newer standard.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 2wav Advocacy for Accessibility and Practice\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We have been active in web accessibility (A11Y) since before it was required. We had employees reliant on assistive technologies as early as 2014, and we have actively advocated for A11Y and published on the topic, including a 2017 technical article on making accessible {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://2wav.com/blogPage/making-mapbox-popups-accessible-2"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
geo-spatial applications
}}}
, and a 2023 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://2wav.com/blogPage/an-interent-for-all"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
guide for developers
}}}
 using the University of Illinois A11Y tools. \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 University of Illinois Accessibility\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The University of Illinois, where we have many roots, was a pioneer in both physical and web accessibility. U of I helped write the WCAG guidelines and created some of the first widely used A11Y tools including:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://accessibleit.disability.illinois.edu/tools/fae"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Functional Accessibility Evaluator (FAE)
}}}
\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab it's companion tool the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/ainspector-wcag/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
AInspector for Firefox
}}}
\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://opena11y.github.io/evaluation-library/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open A11Y Library
}}}
, which these and other tools are based.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These are the primary tools used by the U of I, which we have largely relied on in the past.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Siteimprove \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We know of three Siteimprove tools for A11Y evaluation:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Online commercial site scanning tools only available to customer accounts. \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A free browser extension for evaluating individual web pages.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab An open source evaluation library named {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/Siteimprove/alfa"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Siteimprove Alfa
}}}
, developed under a grant from the European Union. Notes in the code indicate that this is used by the Siteimprove browser extension, and likely the commerial tools. This library is under active development and is updated frequently. It is likely more up-to-date than either the browser extension or the online scanner.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We have compared results from these tools:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The browser extension and the online scanner generally return very similar results, {\i other than violations incorrectly reported by the scanner (described below)}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/Siteimprove/alfa"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Siteimprove Alfa
}}}
 library is slightly more strict. It finds a few violations that are not reported by the extension or online scanner. This is probably due to its frequent updates.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The browser extension and online scanner misidentify a few issues, for example, miscalculating the visible size of some elements. {\i We changed the sites to accommodate these idiosycrasies.} \sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Siteimprove Online Scanner & Browser Extension\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Siteimprove online site scanner appears to be the primary evaluation tool being used by IDNR. We have no direct access to this tool, and were advised to spot-check our pages using the free browser extension. Using the extension, we found many differences between the Siteimprove results and our usual tools. However, manually spot-checking all 2000+ pages is not practical, hence our repeated requests for access to the whole-site online scanner.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Siteimprove Scanner Difficulties\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Reports we received from the Siteimprove online scan indicate that the scanner does not let web pages fully form before evaluating the content. Many modern web applications dynamically construct or enhance the page in the browser itself after raw content from the webserver has been loaded. The rendered page is what human users and assistive technologies interact with. This practice is commonly called {\i hydration}, and it is present in most modern websites built with current generation frameworks such as Next, Nuxt, Angular, Meteor, or Ember. \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some Siteimprove reports include temporary access to an inspector which shows the exact content evaluated by the tool. The inspector clearly shows page content before hydration by the browser, and therefore finds issues which are not present in the real web page. \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Simple Example of a Misidentified Violation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Siteimprove report for Hunt Illinois shows an error titled: "Visible label and accessible name do not match". The Siteimprove inspector for one instance of this error on the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://huntillinois.org/turkey/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Hunt Illinois Turkey
}}}
 page shows HTML which includes an improper {\b aria-label} attribute (colored in red for emphasis):\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\pict\pngblip\picw800\pich493\picwgoal16000\pichgoal9860 }\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The {\i actual} HTML for this page as rendered in a browser does {\i not} contain this attribute (shown here in a browser inspector):\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\pict\pngblip\picw696\pich349\picwgoal13920\pichgoal6980 }\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://huntillinois.org/turkey/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Hunt Illinois Turkey
}}}
 page passes evaluation by both the Siteimprove browser extension and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/Siteimprove/alfa"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Siteimprove Alfa
}}}
. It fails the online scanner because the actual page content is not being evaluated. \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\pict\pngblip\picw800\pich440\picwgoal16000\pichgoal8800 }\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 A Site Scanner Using Siteimprove's Alfa Evaluator\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Manually spot-checking individual pages with a browser extension is not a practical path to compliance for a sites totalling over 2,000 pages. We needed a tool that could evaluate every page \u8212- using the same Siteimprove Alfa evaluation engine \u8212- against a fully rendered page.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 No such tool existed, so we built one.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The tool, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/anderson-2wav/alfa-a11y-scan"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
alfa-a11y-scan
}}}
, is an open-source command-line utility developed by 2wav. It accepts an XML sitemap URL or a list of URLs, fetches each page in a headless Chromium browser (via Microsoft Playwright), waits for JavaScript to execute and the Document Object Model (DOM) to fully hydrate, then passes the rendered document to the Siteimprove Alfa evaluation library. Results are aggregated into structured reports in CSV, Excel, JSON, or HTML format.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The tool is released under the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.gnu.org/licenses/agpl-3.0.en.html"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
AGPL-3.0
}}}
 open-source license. It was developed by 2wav with only our own resources, for use by our clients and other organizations facing the similar challenges with the April 2026 deadline.\par}
